%I A396194 #25 Jun 04 2026 13:19:45
%S A396194 2,3,7,7,59,59,167,167,167,6523,11492,21889,21889,21889,581700,672928,
%T A396194 689193,2199414,2199414,2199414,2199414,2199414,2199414,2199414,
%U A396194 2199414,2199414
%N A396194 a(n) = smallest index t such that the binary expansions of A394166(t) and A394166(t+1) both end in at least n zeros.
%C A396194 Clarification: If a(n) = t then A394166(t) and A394166(t+1) must both be divisible by 2^n. However, they are not required to be divisible by the same power of 2.
%C A396194 A proof that this sequence is infinite would establish that A394166 contains every nonnegative integer.
%H A396194 N. J. A. Sloane, <a href="/A396192/a396192.txt">Table of first 10000 terms of A394166 right-justified followed by n</a>
%e A396194 The initial terms of A394166 (in binary) are:
%e A396194 ...........A394166(n)..n
%e A396194                      0 0
%e A396194                      1 1
%e A396194                     10 2
%e A396194                    100 3
%e A396194                   1000 4
%e A396194                    101 5
%e A396194                   1010 6
%e A396194                  10000 7
%e A396194                 100000 8
%e A396194                     11 9
%e A396194                 100001 10
%e A396194                 110000 11
%e A396194              100000000 12
%e A396194 so a(1) = 2, a(2) = 3, and a(3) = a(4) = 7.
%Y A396194 Cf. A394166, A396188, A396484.
%Y A396194 See A396195 for this sequence with duplicates omitted.
%K A396194 nonn,more,changed
%O A396194 1,1
